  "title": "Produce Liveliness Industrially",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3d4c27fec6c81157",
      "text": "[…], the separation of head and hand continues to exist today. For capital, the head, stomach and heart of the wage laborer remain mere disruptive factors in the otherwise smoothly running production process. And, of course, even today values continue to arise only as a result of the exploitation of the worker in the factory – the expenditure of his concrete vitality and its transformation into generally equal, abstract labor quanta is still a prerequisite for commodity production at all. (This liveliness can possibly be produced industrially one day: But as soon as liveliness can be produced artificially, there is no longer any limit to the process of undercutting the price for the exploitation of this liveliness, and this means that industrially produced liveliness cannot be value-forming). The appearance that it is becoming increasingly difficult to separate manual from mental labor (or 'productive' from 'unproductive' labor) empirically and sensually is, like any first glance, no argument against the continued existence of the separation of hand and head as the basis of capitalist production. No one would even think of denying that water contains oxygen atoms just because they cannot directly detect the oxygen atoms in water."
